@tayloramurphy and friends are trying to understand UI adoption/usage and it appears we're using google analytics to collect some anonymous opt-in metrics in the UI. However, the data we're receiving appears to be limited to vanilla page view events. 

To collect analytics and inject the ga tracker we're using [vue-analytics](https://www.npmjs.com/package/vue-analytics). Considering what @tayloramurphy shared in the GA console and based on the fact that I don't see any use beyond https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/webapp/src/utils/setupAnalytics.js we're probably not actually capturing much beyond basic pageviews.

vue-analytics does support custom events but I checked a few spots and ran a few searches (v-ga, $ga, etc) but didn't find any occurrences of those in the web app. I don't think we're firing any additional events today in the UI.

Since vue-analytics is no longer maintained anyway, we should consider switching either to Google Tag Manager ([vue-gtag](https://github.com/MatteoGabriele/vue-gtag)?) or could consider a switch to Snowplow [(via BrowserTracker?)](https://docs.snowplowanalytics.com/docs/collecting-data/collecting-from-own-applications/javascript-trackers/browser-tracker/).

@tayloramurphy do y'all have a bias or preference here on which route we should take (GA vs Snowplow)?
